{"title":"Tour de France climbs: Col du Glandon, the Alpine appetiser that serves up a feast","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/col-du-glandon-cycling","date":1690804625000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/col-du-glandon-cycling\">Tour de France climbs: Col du Glandon, the Alpine appetiser that serves up a feast</a></p>\n\n<p>The 24.1km thread of road that weaves up the southern flanks of the Col du Glandon presents an ever-shifting photo reel of <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/best-cycling-french-alps\" target=\"_blank\">Alpine peaks</a>, forested slopes, crashing waterfalls and glittering reservoirs, culminating in a euphoric summit-top panorama that stretches all the way to the giant ice-white Mont Blanc.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Situated between the Belledonne, Grandes Rousses and Arvan-Villards mountains, the 1,924m Glandon is twinned with the 2,067m <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/col-de-la-croix-de-fer-climb-guide\" target=\"_blank\">Col de la Croix de Fer</a>, which can be accessed along the same southern roads, before you simply divert east for the final 3km stretch to the neighbouring summit. </p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/tour-de-france-fans-2023\">Basque-ing in the glory: Bilbao’s Tour de France 2023 fans</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/best-cycling-french-alps\">Best places to cycle in the French Alps</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-route-live-tv-guide-startlist-stage-by-stage\">Men’s Tour de France 2023: Stage-by-stage preview and everything you need to know</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article></div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <span></span><span></span><span></span>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        </div>\n\n\n<p>The two fabled cols are together known as the Orthrus of the Alps, after the two-headed dog of Greek mythology, with the twin fangs of rock ready to gnaw at the legs of any cyclist who dares to venture here.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Not just a warm-up act</h2>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-02-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Col du Glandon\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-02-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-02-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-02-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-02-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-02-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-02-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-02-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-02-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-02.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>Juan Trujillo Andrades / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>Part of the Dauphiné Alps, which erupt out of the Savoie region of France, the hulking Glandon has graced the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-route-live-tv-guide-startlist-stage-by-stage\" target=\"_blank\">Tour de France</a> on 14 occasions. The gruellingly long southern route packs in 1,152m of vertical ascent and some surprisingly steep ramps. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>But this route’s richly photogenic landscapes and gentle average gradient of 4.8% have ensured that the Glandon is often regarded, surprisingly and inaccurately, as something of an <em>amuse-bouche</em>: a palate-awakening Alpine appetiser to be savoured before the hearty main course is served on the Glandon’s steeper, flashier neighbours, such as <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-2022-alpe-d-huez\" target=\"_blank\">Alpe d’Huez</a> in the south or the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/col-de-la-madeleine\" target=\"_blank\">Col de la Madeleine</a> in the north.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-03-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Col du Glandon\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-03-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-03-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-03-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-03-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-03-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-03-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-03-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-03-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-03.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>The first half of the climb abounds with hairpins, which top out at around 11%.</figcaption><figcaption>Juan Trujillo Andrades / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>For Tour riders, the Glandon has often been the penultimate climb before a summit-top finish on Alpe d’Huez. And for recreational riders, the col is well-known as the first leg-warmer on the La Marmotte sportive.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Although the col is popular with cyclists, there is no summit-top ski resort like in nearby Alpe d’Huez or <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/classic-climbs-les-deux-alpes\" target=\"_blank\">Les Deux Alpes</a>, ensuring this epic climb feels like a more authentic escape into the wild beauty of the Alps. Even as the legs burn, the road allows you to admire the rocky peaks and the shimmering streams that accompany you as you rise into the clouds.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-04-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Col du Glandon\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-04-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-04-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-04-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-04-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-04-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-04-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-04-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-04-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-04.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>The dam known as the Barrage de Grand Maison alerts you to the fact you’re about to pass the lake.</figcaption><figcaption>Juan Trujillo Andrades / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>But don’t be fooled. Relentlessly long and physically draining, the col has proven to be a quietly decisive obstacle in many key stages in the Tour’s history, ever since its first appearance in 1947. Belgian <em>grimpeur</em> <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-history-lucien-van-impe\" target=\"_blank\">Lucien Van Impe</a> is the rider most closely associated with the Glandon, having been first over the col three times, in 1977, 1981 and 1983, on the way to three of his six polka dot jerseys. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>On Stage 17 of the 1977 Tour, the Belgian shed Bernard Thevenet, Joop Zoetemelk and Hennie Kuiper with a series of brutal accelerations on the Glandon, before being wiped out by a TV car on the way up Alpe d’Huez. The pint-sized climber recovered to claim the mountains jersey five days later.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-05-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Col du Glandon\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-05-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-05-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-05-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-05-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-05-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-05-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-05-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-05-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-05.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>Juan Trujillo Andrades / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>In 1990 <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/cyclist-magazine-podcast-episode-23-the-greg-lemond-special\" target=\"_blank\">Greg LeMond</a>’s heroic efforts in hanging onto a dangerous breakaway on the Glandon helped seal his third and final Tour victory. The col is also known for its lead role on Stage 10 of the 2001 Tour, when Jan Ullrich launched a vicious attack as his rival Lance Armstrong feigned fatigue, before the American surged past him on the climb to Alpe d’Huez.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Soak up the scenery</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The Glandon can be climbed from multiple directions: a 21.9km climb from the north (La Chambre, 6.76%); a 30km climb from the east (Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne, 5.07%) or the 24.1km climb from the south (Barrage du Verney, 4.8%). The northern route is steeper, with a final 2km stretch at 10-13%, but the southern route has the most expansive and varied scenery, and is the one recreational riders follow when taking on La Marmotte.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-06-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Col du Glandon\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-06-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-06-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-06-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-06-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-06-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-06-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-06-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-06-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-06.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>The road away from the Lac de Grand Maison will lead you to the most exposed section of the ascent, and the col will soon appear on the horizon.</figcaption><figcaption>Juan Trujillo Andrades / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>The climb from the south begins in the village of Allemond, just north of Le Bourg-d’Oisans, at the foot of the Belledonne mountains. Here campsites and auberges sit close to the sparkling waters of the Barrage (dam) du Verney, whose vast reservoir hosts the swim section of the Alpe d’Huez triathlon. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Launching your siege of the col, you will pedal past the dam then plunge into thick forests of beech, birch, aspen, willow, fir and spruce that cling to the steep flanks on both sides of the road. It’s a beautifully tranquil start to the ride, taking you past trickling rivers, piles of logs and moss-covered rocks.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-07-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Col du Glandon\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-07-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-07-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-07-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-07-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-07-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-07-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-07-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-07-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-07.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>The bridge over Le Rieu Claret river marks the boundary between Isere and Savoie.</figcaption><figcaption>Juan Trujillo Andrades / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>The southern route is endlessly varied, and a few kilometres later you face an unexpected 10.3% kick, followed by stretches at 9.8% and 8.2%. Then comes a short downhill respite into a valley, where the road disappears into the steep folds of the surrounding peaks. Make the most of it because next comes 11.1% and 10.2% ramps, before a gentle rhythm settles back in.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/subscriptions\"><img width=\"842\" height=\"297\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/04/clickable-subs-promo3.jpg\" alt=\"Subscribe to Cyclist Magazine\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/04/clickable-subs-promo3.jpg 842w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/04/clickable-subs-promo3-300x106.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/04/clickable-subs-promo3-768x271.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/04/clickable-subs-promo3-750x265.jpg 750w\" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>Soon you divert east, passing above steep rock ledges towards the huge embankment dam known as Barrage de Grand Maison. From a distance the dam looks like a sheer, vertical grey monolith, but as you ride closer you see that the face of the dam is gently sloping and zigzagged by access tracks for vehicles.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-08-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Col du Glandon\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-08-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-08-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-08-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-08-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-08-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-08-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-08-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-08-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-08.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>On the dark, higher slopes of the Glandon.</figcaption><figcaption>Juan Trujillo Andrades / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>Past the dam you’re met by the mesmerising Lac de Grand Maison. It is one of the most stunning sections of this climb, with the jagged peaks of the Aiguilles de l’Argentière looming to your left and the vast turquoise reservoir to your right. When you glance back over your shoulder the lake seems to disappear into the blue sky beyond, like a vast, high-mountain infinity pool.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Heading for the summit</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Before long you catch a first glimpse of the col on the horizon. This is the most exposed section of the climb as you weave through Alpine meadows dotted with small huts and scattered rocks. </p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-09-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Col du Glandon\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-09-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-09-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-09-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-09-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-09-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-09-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-09-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-09-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-09.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>Juan Trujillo Andrades / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>The headwinds can be fierce and the landscape is a false flat that plays with your mind. But seeing the col inching closer will lift you, and you eventually reach a green-shuttered restaurant where the road forks right to the Col de la Croix de Fer and left to the Glandon. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>This is a richly historic high-altitude terrain. Coins etched with the face of Roman Emperor Caligula have been found on the col, which was an important route for the Roman army, and you pass a memorial to the Oisans maquis, a guerrilla branch of the French resistance that halted a German advance here in August 1944. </p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-10-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Col du Glandon\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-10-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-10-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-10-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-10-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-10-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-10-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-10-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-10-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/col-du-glandon-10.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>The Chalet Col du Glandon restaurant marks the turning point: left to the Glandon or right to the Croix de Fer.</figcaption><figcaption>Juan Trujillo Andrades / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>But when you finally reach the summit, and enjoy the spellbinding panorama across the Belledonne mountains, the Col de la Madeleine and Mont Blanc, you will be proud to have written your own personal slice of history by ascending this fabled Tour colossus. Devouring an <em>amuse-bouche</em> has never felt so satisfying.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>• This article originally appeared in issue 140 of Cyclist magazine. <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/subscriptions\" target=\"_blank\">Click here to subscribe</a></strong></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/col-du-glandon-cycling\">Tour de France climbs: Col du Glandon, the Alpine appetiser that serves up a feast</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a>.</p>","author":"mdonlevy","siteTitle":"Cyclist.co.uk","siteHash":"561486e7070fa5351de9318ad0fa26c2a39332acba5fc7c7d1694a01d53d431e","entryHash":"47451ad5addeeb6eed378a20ffe894eceb5ad7661d9fddb2c4718a0eb9e9be70","category":"Cycling"}